### Standard enthalpy change of formation, \(\Delta H_{\mathrm{t}}^{\mathrm{\varphi}}\)

The standard enthalpy change of formation, \(\Delta H_{\mathrm{t}}^{\mathrm{\varphi}}\), is the **energy change** when **1 mole of a substance in its standard state** is formed from its **constituent elements in their standard states**, at a specified temperature, usually 298 K.

e.g. \(\gamma_{\mathrm{z}}\mathrm{H_{2}(g)}+\gamma_{\mathrm{z}}\mathrm{I_{2}(s)} \rightarrow\) HI(g) \(\Delta H_{\mathrm{t}}^{\mathrm{\varphi}}\)= +26.5 kJ mol-1

2C(s) + 3H_2(g) + \(\gamma_{\mathrm{z}}\mathrm{O_{2}(g)}\rightarrow\) C_2H_5OH(0) \(\Delta H_{\mathrm{t}}^{\mathrm{\varphi}}\)= -298 kJ mol-1

The standard enthalpy change of formation of **elements** in their standard state (at 1 bar) is **zero**.

e.g. \(Cl_{\mathrm{z}}\mathrm{(g)}\rightarrow Cl_{\mathrm{z}}\mathrm{(g)}\)\(\Delta H_{\mathrm{t}}^{\mathrm{\varphi}}\)= 0

\(\Delta H_{\mathrm{t}}^{\mathrm{\varphi}}\) is a measure of the energetic stability of a substance relative to its constituent elements.

