The heat change, \(q\), can be calculated using the following formula:

\begin{tabular}{|l|} \hline \(q\) = heat change (unit: J) \\ positive (+) if heat is gained from the surroundings by the system \\ negative (-) if heat is lost to the surroundings from the system \\ \(q=-mc\Delta T\) & \(m\) = mass of solution (unit: g) \\ \(c\) = specific heat capacity of water (unit: J g\({}^{-1}\) K\({}^{-1}\)) \\ \(\Delta T\) = temperature change of solution (unit: K or \({}^{0}\)C) \\ = final temperature of solution - **initial** temperature of solution \\ \hline \end{tabular}

The **specific heat capacity**, \(c\), is defined as the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of 1 g of the substance by 1 K. The SI unit of specific heat capacity is J g\({}^{-1}\) K\({}^{-1}\).

Sometimes, the heat capacity of the substance is given instead. The **heat capacity**, \(C\), is defined as the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of a certain mass of the substance by 1 K (or 1 \({}^{0}\)C). The SI unit for heat capacity is J K\({}^{-1}\). To calculate the heat change, we use the following equation:

\begin{tabular}{|l|} \hline \(q\) = heat change (unit: J) \\ positive (+) if heat is gained from the surroundings by the system \\ negative (-) if heat is lost to the surroundings from the system \\ \(q=-C\Delta T\) & C = heat capacity of solution (unit: J K\({}^{-1}\)) \\ \(\Delta T\) = temperature change of solution (unit: K or \({}^{0}\)C) \\ = final temperature of solution - **initial** temperature of solution \\ \hline \end{tabular}

Since we define enthalpy change of reaction (\(\Delta H\)) for every one mole of the _limiting reagent or a specific substance_ identified in the definition, we can calculate the **enthalpy change of reaction (\(\Delta H\))** by using the following equation:

\[\text{enthalpy change of reaction},\ \Delta H_{t}=\frac{q}{n}=\frac{-mc\Delta T}{ \text{amount of limiting reagent / specified substance}}\]

The sign of \(\Delta H\) denotes whether the reaction is exothermic (_i.e._ energy lost to surroundings) or endothermic (_i.e._ energy gained from surroundings). If the reaction is exothermic, \(\Delta H_{t}\) will be negative. If the reaction is endothermic, \(\Delta H_{t}\) will be positive.

